Executive Summary

This repository documents my hands-on practice using OWASP Juice Shop in a controlled HackSmarter lab environment.

The focus of this session was not aggressive exploitation, but building a stable and repeatable testing architecture while validating:

VPN connectivity

Target reachability

Proxy configuration

Burp Suite setup

Java runtime compatibility

Firewall interaction with interception tools

This lab reinforced that environment stability is foundational to effective web application pentesting.

Lab Objective

Practice the core web application testing workflow:

Connect to lab network via VPN

Verify target reachability

Configure Burp Suite proxy

Intercept HTTP traffic

Analyze request/response behavior

Target: OWASP Juice Shop
Tools: Kali Linux (WSL), OpenVPN, Burp Suite Community Edition

VPN Connection Validation

Start OpenVPN:

sudo openvpn foundations_of_web_a.ovpn

Successful connection output:

TUN/TAP device tun0 opened
net_addr_v4_add: 10.200.36.146/16 dev tun0
Initialization Sequence Completed

Interpretation:

Tunnel interface created

IP assigned

Routing active

Target Reachability Testing
ICMP Verification
ping 10.1.139.16

Example response:

64 bytes from 10.1.139.16: icmp_seq=1 ttl=62 time=21.3 ms

Confirmed:

Target reachable through VPN

HTTP Service Check
curl -I http://10.1.139.16

Example response:

HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8
X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN

Confirmed:

Web application running

Security headers present

Java & Burp Compatibility Issue

Initial attempt using OpenJDK 11:

java.lang.UnsupportedClassVersionError:
class file version 65.0

Interpretation:

Burp build compiled for newer Java runtime

OpenJDK 11 incompatible

Switched to Java 21:

sudo update-alternatives --config java
java -version

Confirmed:

openjdk version "21.0.9"

Lesson:
Toolchain compatibility must be validated before troubleshooting application behavior.

Proxy & Firewall Configuration

Final stable setup:

Burp Suite running on Windows

Proxy listener: 127.0.0.1:8080

Windows Firewall explicitly allowing:
C:\Program Files\BurpSuiteCommunity\BurpSuiteCommunity.exe

Browser traffic routed through local proxy

This separation (WSL for VPN, Windows for Burp GUI) resolved GUI instability and routing conflicts.

Key Lessons Learned

Environment misconfiguration can mimic application failure

VPN routing must be validated before proxy debugging

Java runtime version impacts security tooling

Local interception tools require proper firewall permissions

Stable architecture reduces troubleshooting fatigue

Not every lab session produces flags.
Some produce foundational engineering clarity.

